content:
Hi all

I am designing a display typeface in Fontlab. It has substitute ligatures for pretty much every letter combination (like A\_A, A\_B, A\_C...etc). I want to put them all as discretionary ligatures. The code at the moment looks like this:

feature dlig {  
 sub A A by A\_A;  
 sub A B by A\_B;  
 sub A C by A\_C;  
 sub A D by A\_D;  
 sub A E by A\_E;  
 sub A F by A\_F;  
 sub A G by A\_G;  
 sub A H by A\_H;  
 sub A I by A\_I;  
 sub A J by A\_J;  
 sub A K by A\_K;  
 sub A L by A\_L;  
 sub A M by A\_M;  
 sub A N by A\_N;  
 sub A O by A\_O;  
 sub A P by A\_P;  
 sub A R by A\_R;  
 sub A S by A\_S;  
 sub A T E by A\_T\_I;  
 sub A T I by A\_T\_E;  
 sub A T by A\_T;  
 sub A U by A\_U;  
 sub A V by A\_V;  
 sub A W by A\_W;  
 sub A X by A\_X;  
 sub A Y by A\_Y;  
 sub A Z by A\_Z;

.......(and will eventually go all the way to Z\_Z)....

} dlig;

I am afraid it may end up being huge and perhaps make the font slow, although it is a display font so most probably it won't be used for huge chunks of text.

Is there any other way to do it? I am not good at scripting and I've searched around but I couldn't find if there is another way to use classes to do it.

Any help will be greatly appreciated.

Thanks!
